        <h1 style="font-size:50px;">List of notable critics of Rodrigo Duterte</h1>
        <h1 style="font-size:16px;">Posted on March 30, 2020</h1>

       <h5>Richard Heydarian</h5>

        <figure>
            <img src="img/richheyd3.jpg" alt="" style="width:25%">
            <figcaption>Photo taken from Richard Heydarian's Facebook account</figcaption>
        </figure>

       <p>Richard Javad Heydarian is a Manila-based academic, having taught political science at Ateneo De Manila University and De La Salle University, Philippines. Heydarian is also a columnist of <i>Philippine Daily Inquirer</i>. Over the course of Duterte administration, Heydarian become one of the critics of Duterte, constantly addressing about the killings during the war on drugs, issues of South China Sea dispute, and others using his Twitter account.</p>

       <h5>Leah Navarro</h5>
       <p>Leah Navarro is a former singer. </p>

        <h5>Agot Isidro</h5>
        <figure>
            <img src="https://secondhandsongs.com/picture/232619" alt="" style="width:25%">
            <figcaption></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>As an artist, Agot Isidro joined to criticize Duterte through Twitter.</p>

        <h5>Francis Pangilinan</h5>
        <figure>
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/3/37/Senkikopangilinan.jpg" alt="" style="width:24%">
            <figcaption></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>Pangilinan won a Senate seat on 2016 elections under the banner of Liberal Party.</p>

        <h5>Leila de Lima</h5>
        <figure>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="" style="width:25%">
            <figcaption></figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>Leila de Lima is known for vocal criticism against Duterte particularly the government's war on drugs and the human rights. The news of <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/23/world/asia/arrest-duterte-leila-de-lima.html">arrest of de Lima for allegedly violating the drug trafficking law</a> on February 23, 2017 shook the nation as well as from the international news outlets. De Lima <a href="http://cnnphilippines.com/news/2017/02/24/leila-de-lima-arrested-over-drug-charges.html">turned herself in the following morning</a> of February 24. She has also been referred to as a 'prisoner of conscience' by numerous international human rights organizations. Efforts made by international human rights advocates to release de Lima from prison have been made throughout the years, but it never came it fruition as the Philippine government did not tackle it.</p>

        <p>During her detention, de Lima regularly made a statement through her letter sent to the media, criticizing various policies of Duterte.</p>

        <h5>Risa Hontiveros</h5>
        <figure>
            <img src="https://img-s-msn-com.akamaized.net/tenant/amp/entityid/BB10gP54.img?h=0&w=720&m=6&q=60&u=t&o=f&l=f&x=505&y=239" alt="" style="width:25%">
            <figcaption></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>A Senator, former representative of Akbayan (2004-2010), women's rights advocate and sister of Pia Hontiveros (the current anchor of CNN Philippines), Hontiveros known for staunch critic of Duterte when it comes to the sexist issues made by the president.</p>

        <h5>Jim Paredes</h5>
        <figure>
            <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn%3AANd9GcSZmEYPid9uAp_oEwiKsv50HgNr1VC2zGHjFC1RU5KFUUU_gVAH&usqp=CAU" alt="" style="width:25%">
            <figcaption></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>Paredes is a member of Apo Hiking Society and a known supporter of Liberal Party candidates, who denounced Duterte as the president.</p>

        <h5>Franklin Drilon</h5>
        <figure>
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/7b/Franklin_Drilon_jun2017.jpg" alt="" style="width:25%">
            <figcaption></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>A Liberal Party Senator, Drilon throws a word against Duterte, known for questioning the ₱50 million budget for the SEA Games cauldron. He lamented that the budget could have been used for other purposes of national importance, such as the construction of classrooms instead. Government officials denied that the budget was overpriced. Nevertheless, the SEA Games proves to be fruitful despite the flaws been addressed on social media before the start of the SEA Games.</p>

        <h5>Bam Aquino</h5>
        <figure>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="" style="width:25%">
            <figcaption></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>Bam Aquino is the cousin of former President Benigno Aquino III. During his Senate career, Aquino made a statement against Duterte for various policies. He was being obsessed by pro-Duterte fan pages, who are looking for negativity against the president. In 2019 elections, he ran again as a Senator under the banner of Otso Diretso, but he was voted out by the public (probably due to his stance against the administration). After he leaves the Senate, several known pro-Duterte fan pages and supporters, for some reason, stopped obsessing Aquino.</p>

        <h5>Antonio Trillanes</h5>
        <figure>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="" style="width:25%">
            <figcaption></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>Trillanes is known for expressing anger against the President through social media. He will not stop <a href="https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/07/19/19/trillanes-blasts-sedition-charges-against-opposition-figures">until he discover the truth of presidential son</a>, Paolo Duterte's link to the illegal drug trade. When his Senate term finishes, he continues to made a statement via video blogging.</p>

        <h5>Cynthia Patag</h5>
        <!----
        <figure>
            <img src="" alt="" style="width:25%">
            <figcaption></figcaption>
        </figure> --->
        <p>A former actress, Patag constantly criticizes the president for various policies through social media.</p>

        <h5>Jover Laurio of Pinoy Ako Blog</h5>
        <figure>
            <img src="img/jover.jpg" alt="" style="width:25%">
            <figcaption>Courtesy of Jover Laurio's Facebook account</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>Jover Laurio constantly throws a shade against Duterte for every move that he made, as well as Mocha Uson, who is controversially known for spreading fake news. You can check her official Twitter account, Pinoy Ako Blog.</p>

        
        <h5>Raissa Robles</h5>
        <figure>
            <img src="img/raissa.jpg" alt="" style="width:25%">
            <figcaption></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>A journalist from Rappler, Robles is known for constantly throws against Duterte and the government.</p>

        <h5>Maria Ressa</h5>
        <figure>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="" style="width:25%">
            <figcaption></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>Ressa, the CEO of Rappler, also hit Duterte and the government through her social media. Her criticism further motivated when the SEC plans to revoke Rappler's license on January 2018 on due to its use of "Philippine Depository Receipts (PDRs)". The decision triggered massive condemnation from militant groups, calling it "the attack on press freedom".</p>
 
        

